go 1.22

use (
	./api
	./newsroom
)

// =============================================================================
// GO WORKSPACE - Development-time module coordination
// =============================================================================
//
// This go.work file defines a workspace that includes both the api and
// newsroom modules. During development, Go automatically uses the local
// versions of these modules instead of fetching from remote repositories.
//
// Benefits of Workspaces:
//
// 1. Local Development: Make changes across modules without publishing
//    - Edit newsroom code, see changes instantly in API
//    - No need for version tags or releases
//    - Rapid iteration during development
//
// 2. Independent Versioning: Each module has its own go.mod
//    - API can be at v1.5.2
//    - Newsroom can be at v0.2.0
//    - Different maturity levels
//    - Different release cadences
//
// 3. Clean Separation: Workspace is development-only
//    - Users don't see or use go.work
//    - They get published versions from module proxy
//    - go.work should NOT be committed (add to .gitignore)
//    - Production builds use go.mod, not go.work
//
// 4. Module Boundaries: Clear separation of concerns
//    - API handles HTTP and storage
//    - Newsroom handles AI summarization
//    - Each can evolve independently
//    - Easy to test in isolation
//
// Commands for workspace management:
//
//   # Initialize a workspace
//   go work init ./api
//
//   # Add another module to workspace
//   go work use ./newsroom
//
//   # List modules in workspace
//   go work edit -print
//
//   # Sync dependencies across workspace
//   go work sync
//
// Directory structure with workspace:
//
//   go-news/
//   ├── go.work          ← Workspace definition (this file)
//   ├── api/
//   │   ├── go.mod       ← API module definition
//   │   ├── go.sum       ← API dependency checksums
//   │   ├── cmd/
//   │   │   └── api/
//   │   │       └── main.go
//   │   └── internal/
//   │       ├── feed/
//   │       ├── reader/
//   │       ├── store/
//   │       └── handlers/
//   └── newsroom/
//       ├── go.mod       ← Newsroom module definition
//       ├── go.sum       ← Newsroom dependency checksums
//       ├── summarizer.go
//       └── cmd/
//           └── newsroom/
//               └── main.go
//
// Workflow example:
//
//   1. Developer edits newsroom/summarizer.go
//   2. Changes are immediately visible in api/
//   3. Run API: cd api && go run ./cmd/api
//   4. API uses local newsroom code automatically
//   5. No version bumps or publishing needed
//
// When to use workspaces:
//
// - Monorepo with multiple related modules
// - Library + example application
// - Microservices that share common packages
// - Plugin architecture with core + plugins
// - Any time you need to develop multiple modules together
//
// When NOT to use workspaces:
//
// - Single module projects (just use go.mod)
// - Unrelated modules that don't interact
// - Third-party dependencies (those come from module proxy)
//
// Production deployment:
//
// When releasing, you:
// 1. Tag and publish newsroom module
//    git tag -a newsroom/v0.2.0 -m "Add AI summarization"
//    git push origin newsroom/v0.2.0
//
// 2. Update API's go.mod to reference published version
//    require github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/go-news/newsroom v0.2.0
//
// 3. Tag and publish API module
//    git tag -a api/v1.5.2 -m "Add summary endpoint"
//    git push origin api/v1.5.2
//
// Users then import your modules normally:
//   import "github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/go-news/api"
//   import "github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/go-news/newsroom"
//
// They get the published versions, not your local dev code.
//
// This workspace pattern is essential for:
// - Clean architecture with module boundaries
// - Independent evolution of components
// - Team collaboration on related modules
// - Maintaining API stability while experimenting with new features
//
// The workspace is your development environment.
// The published modules are your production artifacts.
// Keep them separate, and you get the best of both worlds.
